📘 Basic Variables
🟢 Introduction
A variable is a named memory location used to store data that can be modified during program execution.
In DSA, variables are the building blocks of algorithms.

🟢 What is a Variable?
A variable stores data
Each variable has:
Name (identifier)
Value
Data Type
Example:
int age = 19;
age → variable name
19 → value
int → data type
🟢 Importance in DSA

Variables are used to:
Store inputs
Perform calculations
Control loops and conditions
Track results

🟢 Basic Data Types
Data Type	Description	Example
int	Integer (whole numbers)	int x = 10;
float	Decimal numbers	float pi = 3.14;
char	Single character	char grade = 'A';
bool	True/False	bool flag = true;

🟢 Declaration & Initialization
Declaration:
int x;
Initialization:
x = 5;
Combined:
int x = 5;

🟢 Rules for Naming Variables
✔ Must start with a letter or _
✔ Cannot start with a number
✔ No spaces allowed
✔ Cannot use reserved keywords

Valid:
total, _count, sum1
Invalid:
1sum, total marks, int

🟢 Memory Concept
Every variable occupies memory
Size depends on data type:
Type	Size
int	4 bytes
char	1 byte
float	4 bytes

👉 Important for Space Complexity in DSA

🟢 Example (C vs Java)

Java
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x = 10;
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}
🟢 Example in DSA
Sum of Two Numbers
int a = 5;
int b = 10;
int sum = a + b;
🟢 Common Mistakes

❌ Using uninitialized variables
❌ Wrong data types
❌ Confusing = and ==
❌ Overflow errors

🟢 Practice Questions
Q1:
int a = 5;
int b = 3;
int c = a + b * 2;

👉 Output?

Q2:

Which is valid variable name?

A) 1num
B) total_sum
C) float
D) total sum
Q3:

Which data type is suitable for storing 3.75?

🟢 Conclusion

Variables are fundamental in programming and DSA.
Understanding them properly is essential before moving to advanced topics like arrays, pointers, and data structures.
